HEADWORD: Rapacity
<hw>Ra*pac"i*ty</hw> <pr>(r⟦adot⟧*p⟦acr⟧s"⟦icr⟧*t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>rapacitas</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>rapacit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Rapacious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The quality of being rapacious; rapaciousness; ravenousness;
<as>as, the <ex>rapacity</ex> of pirates; the <ex>rapacity</ex> of
wolves.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or practice of extorting or exacting by
oppressive injustice; exorbitant greediness of gain.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>rapacity</xex> of some ages.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sprat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Raparee</ent>⟦br⟧
